# Flowspec Specification Corpus — Decision Log
# Every significant decision made during the spec interview, with rationale.

---
decision: "Tree-sitter-first, no LSP"
date: 2026-03-10
area: architecture
rationale: |
  TDF 5-way synthesis. LSP is someone else's semantic layer — complete but
  opaque, heavy to manage (process lifecycle for 3 different language servers),
  and different for every language. Tree-sitter + custom semantic resolution
  gives Flowspec ownership of its analysis pipeline, uniform multi-language
  support, and the speed profile needed for incremental analysis. No external
  processes spawned during analysis. LSP was fully removed from the v1
  architecture — not even as optional enrichment.
alternatives_considered:
  - "LSP-first with tree-sitter supplementing (original design doc)"
  - "Tree-sitter-first with optional LSP enrichment"
  - "Pure tree-sitter, no LSP at all (chosen)"

---
decision: "Persistent in-memory graph with disk serialization"
date: 2026-03-10
area: architecture
rationale: |
  TDF 4-way synthesis. The original "no database" constraint was about avoiding
  external dependencies, not avoiding persistence. Single-symbol trace queries
  and incremental analysis inherently need a queryable, persistent data
  structure. Every successful incremental analysis tool uses this pattern —
  in-memory index with disk serialization. The YAML manifest is an export
  format, not the primary data structure.
alternatives_considered:
  - "YAML manifest as primary data (original design doc)"
  - "External database (too heavy)"
  - "In-memory graph with binary cache (chosen)"

---
decision: "Python, JavaScript, and Rust for v1"
date: 2026-03-10
area: architecture
rationale: |
  User explicitly requested all three for v1. Python first (Mozart is Python),
  JavaScript for broad applicability, Rust because Flowspec is Rust and
  enables dogfooding. Original design doc had Rust-only for phase 1.

---
decision: "Dual AGPL-3.0 + Commercial license"
date: 2026-03-10
area: constraints
rationale: |
  Matches Mozart's licensing model. Enables open-source use while supporting
  commercial integration. All dependencies must have AGPL-compatible licenses.

---
decision: "Rust implementation language"
date: 2026-03-10
area: constraints
rationale: |
  Tree-sitter has mature Rust bindings. Cargo workspace gives library + CLI
  split naturally. Single binary distribution. Strong serialization ecosystem
  (serde, bincode). Performance tier appropriate for incremental analysis.
  User confirmed after considering C/C++ (ClamAV background).

---
decision: "Failure-pattern diagnostics, not graph-theory terms"
date: 2026-03-10
area: diagnostics
rationale: |
  TDF 5-way synthesis. AI agents understand failure patterns better than graph
  theory. "Unwired feature" is actionable. "Isolated subgraph" requires the
  agent to figure out what it means. 13 diagnostic patterns identified,
  organized by what went wrong in terms agents can act on.

---
decision: "Confidence-scored diagnostics, false-negative-averse"
date: 2026-03-10
area: diagnostics
rationale: |
  User stated false negatives are the worst failure. Report everything above
  minimum confidence with confidence levels (high, moderate, low). Consumers
  triage by confidence. Never suppress a finding to reduce false positives.

---
decision: "Summary-first manifest with abbreviated field names"
date: 2026-03-10
area: manifest-schema
rationale: |
  Agents rarely dig past what's first presented to them. Summary section
  (~2K tokens) gives full structural overview. Abbreviated field names
  (vis, sig, loc) save tokens. Complete manifest for 50K-line project
  targets under 500KB.

---
decision: "stdout default output"
date: 2026-03-10
area: cli
rationale: |
  stdout is natural for AI agent consumption (capture and inject into
  context). --output flag available for workflows that don't support
  piping or redirects. All logs go to stderr to keep stdout pipe-safe.

---
decision: "Kill flowspec lint command"
date: 2026-03-10
area: cli
rationale: |
  Overlaps with diagnose. Layer violations and contract mismatches are
  diagnostic patterns, not lint rules. One command (diagnose) with
  --checks filtering is cleaner than two commands with overlapping scope.

---
decision: "89% test coverage target with adversarial testing"
date: 2026-03-10
area: quality
rationale: |
  User wants Mozart-level test discipline from the start. 89% coverage
  minimum. Every diagnostic must have true-positive, true-negative, and
  adversarial tests. Broken tests never deferred. Issues always filed.
  Agents must actively try to break their own work.

---
decision: "One multi-language fixture project"
date: 2026-03-10
area: quality
rationale: |
  Single fixture with Python, JS, and Rust code. Known properties per
  language for validation. More realistic than per-language fixtures —
  real projects mix languages.

---
decision: "Data-oriented architecture inspired by ECS"
date: 2026-03-10
area: conventions
rationale: |
  TDF synthesis. User's ECS instinct points at the right mental model:
  symbols as IDs in flat tables, properties as data, analyzers as functions
  that query data. Graph is passive data store, analysis logic is separate.
  Implemented as idiomatic Rust (not an ECS framework) — concrete types,
  traits only at real boundaries.

---
decision: "Linux primary, loose macOS support, no Windows"
date: 2026-03-10
area: constraints
rationale: |
  User's environment is Linux (WSL2). No macOS hardware for CI testing.
  Write portable code by default but don't spend effort on macOS-specific
  issues. Fix macOS bugs if reported and fix is straightforward. Windows
  explicitly not supported.

---
decision: "SARIF output format for CI integration"
date: 2026-03-10
area: integration
rationale: |
  SARIF (Static Analysis Results Interchange Format) opens deeper
  integration with GitHub Code Scanning, VS Code, and other tools.
  Added as output format alongside YAML, JSON, and summary.

---
decision: "Flowspec and codegraph-rust are fully independent"
date: 2026-03-10
area: integration
rationale: |
  Different tools solving different problems. Flowspec: batch structural
  analysis. codegraph: interactive knowledge graph queries. No integration
  path needed. Users can run both independently.

---
decision: "Async with tokio throughout"
date: 2026-03-10
area: constraints
rationale: |
  User explicitly requested async/tokio patterns. Async for I/O-bound
  operations (file reading, cache, watch mode). Tree-sitter parsing is
  CPU-bound — use spawn_blocking. Dependency policy: prefer mature,
  well-maintained crates, no hard limit on count.

---
decision: "Performance targets: <7min first run, <1min incremental"
date: 2026-03-10
area: constraints
rationale: |
  For a 50K-line codebase. Under 7 minutes ideal for first run, 10
  pushes it. Under 1 minute for incremental. Under 5 seconds for
  single-symbol trace from cached graph.

---
decision: "Defer duplication and asymmetric_handling diagnostics to v1.1"
date: 2026-03-27
area: diagnostics
rationale: |
  Both patterns have been carried for 10+ development cycles without progress.
  duplication (detecting repeated code patterns, near-duplicates, copy-paste)
  requires AST-level structural comparison — tree hashing and normalized
  subtree matching. The current graph architecture stores symbols and edges
  but not AST structure. Would require either storing normalized AST subtrees
  in the graph or re-parsing during analysis, neither of which fits the
  parse-once-query-many architecture.

  asymmetric_handling (detecting inconsistent error handling, missing cleanup
  paths, unbalanced resource management) requires control flow analysis —
  CFG construction and path enumeration. The current graph has call edges
  and reference edges but no control flow edges. Would require a new edge
  type or a separate CFG structure.

  Both remain on the roadmap as post-v1 work items. They are not removed —
  just explicitly deferred with documented rationale. v1 ships with 11
  active diagnostic patterns out of the original 13.
alternatives_considered:
  - "Implement partial detection with heuristics (rejected — high FP risk, violates confidence-scored diagnostics principle)"
  - "Remove from roadmap entirely (rejected — both are valuable patterns, just need infrastructure that v1 doesn't have)"
  - "Defer to v1.1 with documented rationale (chosen)"
